THE RISK:
{
 "id": "statista-scale-colo-scope-inflation",
 "title": "One vendor's unverified 'colocation and scale-colocation' definition is both the geo split and a hidden multiplier inside tamBase — normalization launders the scope error out of sight",
 "narrative": "Every geo node and the 39.8% CE-of-Europe step inside tamBase come from a single Statista series whose scope no second vendor reproduces. The corpus shows the series runs hot: summed 2024 Statista country colo (~7.6GW) exceeds CBRE's 5.8GW figure for ALL European DC capacity, and PMR's CEE numbers imply a regional base ~5× smaller than the Statista-derived one. Because the seven geo shares are normalized to 1.00, the axis looks self-consistent no matter how wrong the underlying series is — but the same series also sets the absolute CE-of-Europe fraction in tamBase, where a scope inflation does not cancel. If 'scale-colocation' quietly includes hyperscale self-build shells or contracted-not-energized capacity, the CE market is being sized off MW that either doesn't exist yet or buys PDUs through channels outside this model.",
 "category": "fact",
 "targetNodes": [
  "tamBase"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "Statista's per-country colocation figures share no verified common scope with any benchmark: the summed 2024 country values (~7.6GW) exceed CBRE's 4,726MW European colo supply and even its 5.8GW total-European-capacity figure, and no second vendor uses the 'colocation and scale-colocation IT power' definition",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-region-denominator#c1",
    "digest:geo-region-denominator#c3",
    "digest:geo-region-denominator#c5"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Independent regional checks confirm the same direction of error: PMR/Atman put Poland at ~200MW commercial and >1/3 of a CEE total ≈600MW, versus the Statista-derived CE-7 base of 3,451MW — meaning the series most plausibly counts capacity classes (self-build shells, contracted pipeline) that do not purchase rack PDUs as modeled",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-PL#c13",
    "digest:geo-PL#c14",
    "ledger:geo.PL"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The CE-7 = 39.8%-of-Europe step in tamBase's derivation was computed on an inflated numerator and denominator of unknown relative bias; recomputing CE's weight on a CBRE-consistent scope shrinks the CE slice of the European base, cutting tamBase below its curated value independent of the global-base and Europe-share disputes — while the normalized geo shares hide that anything moved",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:tamBase",
    "ledger:geo.DE",
    "digest:geo-region-denominator#c5"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "Each geo node individually shows a cross-check (BMWK, DDCA, CBRE Suisse, Mordor) and several carry 'triangulated' maturity, so the axis reads as well-verified. But every cross-check uses a DIFFERENT scope, and normalizing shares to 1.00 makes the split immune to absolute-level errors — the one place the absolute level still matters, the CE-of-Europe factor inside tamBase, inherits the error invisibly because it sits inside a derivation expression rather than on a slider.",
 "expectedObviousness": "low",
 "falsifier": "Statista's methodology note (or a second vendor such as DC Byte or CBRE) reproducing the per-country 2025 colocation MW figures within ~15% under an explicitly identical definition, confirming the CE-7/Europe ratio survives a scope-consistent recomputation.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.45,
  "rationale": "The sum-exceeds-total discrepancy against CBRE is arithmetically documented in the corpus, and the PMR/CEE contradiction is independent corroboration; the uncertainty is whether the inflation is uniform across countries (in which case the CE ratio partially survives) or concentrated in scale-colo-heavy markets [evidence revision: Statista's own methodology note confirms 'scale colocation' includes 'powered shells' — a category that maps directly to the hypothesis's 'self-build shells / contracted-not-energized capacity' that would not purchase rack PDUs as modeled. This is a stronger, more direct confirmation of the scope-inflation premise than previously available, and CBRE's 4,726MW/5.8GW figures confirm the sum-exceeds-total arithmetic. Raising from 0.35. Not higher because the residual uncertainty — whether the inflation is uniform (CE ratio partly survives) or concentrated in scale-colo-heavy markets — remains unresolved, and no source reproduces per-country MW under an identical definition to quantify the tamBase impact.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.35
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "tamBase",
   "op": "scale",
   "value": 0.8,
   "note": "CE-of-Europe factor recomputed on a CBRE-consistent colocation scope; geo shares left intact since normalization absorbs the per-country error"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "CBRE Europe Data Centres quarterly country/market supply figures vs Statista's same-year per-country values",
   "where": "CBRE 'Europe Data Centres Figures' quarterly PDF releases (Frankfurt, Amsterdam, Warsaw, Zurich, Vienna market pages)",
   "threshold": "CBRE country supply persistently <60% of Statista's figure for the same country and year",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Country-level MW tables from the gated EUDCA 'State of European Data Centres 2026' report",
   "where": "EUDCA report release and member briefings",
   "threshold": "EUDCA CE country totals implying CE-7 <30% of Europe on a consistent scope",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Purchase one scope-consistent second dataset (DC Byte or CBRE country series) and recompute the CE-of-Europe factor and all seven geo shares from a single definition",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "tamBase",
   "note": "One dataset fixes both the hidden multiplier in tamBase and the geo axis simultaneously — highest structural VOI per euro after the IndexBox report"
  },
